ALL OF OUR HOSES ARE CHECKED  ON A REGULAR BASIS AND EACH OF OUR DRIVERS PERFORM A PRE TRIP, WHICH ENTAILS CHECKING THE STRUCTURE OF THE HOSE TO AVOID ANY UNNECESSARY PROBLEMS. DRIVER SAFETY AND CONCERN FOR THE ENVIRONMENT ARE (2) ISSUES WE PAY CLOSE ATTENTION TO. IF A HOSE IS FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE, A DIFFERENT HOSE IS GIVEN TO THE DRIVER.

A BULK DELIVERY WAS MADE BY AIR PRODUCTS TRANSPORT TRUCK @ 19:56 3/3/03 (AN AFTER-HOURS DELIVERY) .  I ARRIVED AT WORK AT 06:20 3/4/03, I WAS FIRST HERE AND NOTICED A HEAVY VAPOR CLOUD AROUND THE BASE OF THE BULK TANK.  ON CLOSER EXAMINATION I DISCOVERED VERY HEAVY VENTING AND ICE BUILD-UP ON BOTTOM OF BULK TANK AND CONCRETE PAD.  I PHONED AIR PRODUCTS FOR ASSISTANCE AND THEY RESPONDED AND ARRIVED AT SITE WITHIN 45 MINUTES.  I THEN SECURED THE AREA KEEPING OTHER ARRIVING EMPLOYEES AT A SAFE DISTANCE.  THE AIR PRODUCTS REPAIRMAN DETERMINED THAT PRESSURE BUILD REGULATOR MALFUNCTIONED CAUSING EXCESSIVE PRESSURE BUILD-UP, THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE OPENED AT 100 PSI TO VENT EXCESS PRESSURE (AS IT SHOULD HAVE).  AIR PRODUCTS REPLACED THE REGULATOR (SEE ATTACHMENT 1 FOR REPAIR DOCUMENTATION).  WE LOST 25" ON 463 GAL. OF LIQ. OXYGEN TO VENTING.

UNKNOWN CAUSE OF PINHOLE

OUTBOUND DRIVER REPORTED CONTAINER LEAKING IN TRAILER LOT. BNSF INSPECTION OF LADING REVEALED PARTIAL SECOND LAYER HAD SHIFTED DUE TO INSUFFICIENT BLOCKING & BRACING, PLUS NO PROPER LAYER SEPARATOR APPLIED. A DRUM FELL INTO VOID CUTTING ANOTHER. ANOTHER DRUM FOUND WITH SIDEWALL CUTS FROM THE SHARP EDGES OF REAR DOOR FRAME. SEVEN DRUMS DENTED BUT DIDN'T LEAK. SPILLED PRODUCT REMEDIATED, LADING ADJUSTED & LEAKING DRUMS OVERPACKED & RETURNED TO LOAD.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DRIVER NOTIFIED THE COMPANY'S HAZMAT DEPT. THAT AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY A PURPLE-MAROON SOLID WAS DISCOVERED UNDERNEATH THE SKID. CONSIGNEE BROKE DOWN THE SKID TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK. CONSIGNEE FOUND THAT A CHOCK/NAILER PUT ON THE PALLET BY THE SHIPPER HAD NAILS PROTRUDING, THE BOTTOM OF THE 1 DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY THE NAIL. CONSIGNEE SWEPT UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND IT WAS NEUTRALIZED BY THE CONSIGNEE USING MAGNESIUM OXIDE. THE DRUM WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: ON MARCH 5, 2003, TRAILER S073039 ARRIVED AT AIR PRODUCTS TO DELIVER APPROXIMATELY 45,000 POUNDS OF NITRIC ACID.  AFTER UNLOADING ABOUT 36000 LBS OF PRODUCTS, THE TRAILER BEGAN TO LEAK FROM A SECTION OF PIPE LOCATED BETWEEN INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES.  APPROXIMATELY 3-5 GALLONS WERE SPILLED WITHIN AIR PRODUCTS CONTAINMENT AREA.  AIR PRODUCTS PLUGGED THE LEAK AND FINISHED UNLOADING THE TRAILER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, TWO LEAKING FIFTY POUND PAPER BAGS WERE DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK.APPROXIMATELY THREE POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE DOCK. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A NAIL PUNCTURE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BAGS, ALONG WITH THE WEIGHT OF BAGS ON TOP CAUSING THE TWO BAGS TO RUPTURE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A DUSTPAN AND WHISKBROOM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND TWO LEAKING BAGS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TWENTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE FREE PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM A PINHOLE IN THE BOTTOM. UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT THE PAIL WAS REMOVER FROM THE SHIPMENT AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK FOR SAFE TRANSIT BACK TO THE SHIPPER. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO THE SAME OVERPACK.

WHILE DRIVING ON I-94 WESTBOUND, THE JEVIC TRUCK DRIVER HAD TO PERFORM AN EMERGENCY BRAKING DUE TO A CAR INTRUDING ON HIS LANE. THE EMERGENCY BRAKING RESULTED IN THE FREIGHT SHIFTING FORWARD. THE BRAKING CAUSED A TOTE TO MOVE FORWARD BREAKING THE LOAD BAR. THE BAR PUNCTURED A DRUM IN FRONT OF IT CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 20-30 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE-BASED PRODUCT TO LEAK. THE DRIVER PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD TO INSPECT HIS FREIGHT AND NOTICED THE LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER CALLED OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WHO IT TURN DISPATCHED A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW. THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT SECURED THE SIDE OF THE ROAD TO ALLOW THE RESPONSE CREW ACCESS TO THE TRAILER. THE RESPONSE CREW, WEARING PERSONNEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.MOVED THE FREIGHT AROUND TO ACCESS THE PUNCTURED DRUM AND WAS ABLE TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE DRUM TO A CLEAN SECONDARY DRUM AND USE ABSORBENTS ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. WHILE THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER WERE BEING HANDLED, ADDITIONAL CREW MEMBERS EXCAVATED  SURFICIAL SOILS AND ROADSIDE TO CONTAINERIZE SODIUM HYDROXIDE COMTAMINATED SOILS.  ONCE THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY WERE SATISFIED WITH THE CLEANUP EFFORTS, THE CLEANUP MATERIAL AND FREIGHT WAS RETURNED TO THE JEVIC FACILITY IN MARKHAM, ILLINOIS FOR INSPECTION. THERE WAS NO FURTHER INCIDENT REGARDING THIS SHIPMENT. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON MAINTAINING PROPER DISTANCE FROM VEHICLES IN FRONT OF HIS TRUCK.

column168: DRIVER WAS GOING DOWN I-16 EAST WHEN HE HEARD A "TIRE POP" HE LOOKED BACK THROUGH THE BACK WINDOW IN THE CAB AND SAW FLAMES AND SMOKE COMING FROM HIS RIGHT SIDE DRIVE ABLE. HE STOPPED HIS UNIT ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE. GOT OUT AND WENT TO THE RIGHT ABLE. THE FLAMES WERE COMING UP IN BETWEEN THE TIRES. HE THEN GOT BACK IN THE CAB AND ATTEMPTED TO OPEN THE RELEASE BUCKET OF THE EXTINGUISHER MOUNTED INSIDE THE CAB. HE WAS UNABLE TO GET THE EXTINGUISHER OUT. THE FIRE CONTINUED TO SPEND CAUSING THE EMERGENCY VENTS TO OPEN THE FIRE IGNITED THE VAPORS SETING DISPERSED THROUGH THE VENT ON TOP OF THE TRAILER.

THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. UPON INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE AND ITS CONTENTS, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A FUEL PUMP WAS LEAKING INSIDE THE BOX. THE SHIPMENT HAD NOT BEEN OFFERED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS AND THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER. I CONTACTED KEN MASSEY, WITH THE MEM/TSA OFFICE AND HE WENT TO VIEW THE PACKAGE AND OPEN AN INVESTIGATION ARRANGEMENTS WERE LATER MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO HAVE THE SHIPMENT MOVED BACK TO HIS LOCATION AFTER THE TSA WAS FINISHED WITH THEIR VIEWING OF THE PACKAGE.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY WAS NOTICED. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A PLASTIC CONTAINER AT APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON CAPACITY. THE LID SEAL ON THE CONTAINER APPARENTLY FAILED IN TRANSIT RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER. THE FIRE FIGHTING SECTION OF THE DOCUMENT SHOWED THE FLASHPOINT TO BE 116'F WHICH IS WELL WITHIN FLAMMABLE LIQUID CLASSIFICATION LIMITS. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKING OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOOD OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION. TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT ALLEN EDWARDS/FAA/DEN/CASFO/BY VOICEMAIL AT 11:30 AM (CST) ON 3/11/2003 AND BY TELEPHONE AT 08:57 (CST) ON 3/13/2003.

column168: CALEB CALLED IN THEY FOUND THE LEAKER.  IT IS A 30-GALLON POLY DRUM OF ULTRA SHEEN CLEAR COAT BLUE; ITEM NUMBER 30000206 AND BILL OF LADING #100-2507943.  THE DRUM SHIFTED FORWARD AND THEN BACK AND CAME OFF ITS SKID.  IT WEDGE BETWEEN ITS SKID AND THE SKID BEHIND IT.  A HOLE WAS PUNCTURED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  AN ESTIMATED 15 GALLONS WAS RELEASED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY, THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF A LEAKING REDUCER GASKET.  THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. DRIVER PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAKING REDUCER GASKET TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. DRIVER REPLACED THE LEAKING REDUCER GASKET TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. CLEAN UP OF THE CONCRETE SURFACE WAS PERFORMED BY THE CONSIGNEE, SOVEREIGN PACKAGING COMPANY OF SEABROOK, NEW HAMPSHIRE.  NO SOIL OR WATER WAS IMPACTED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE CONSIGNEE, SOVEREIGN PACKAGING COMPANY OF SEABROOK, NEW HAMPSHIRE WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED DURING THE CLEAN UP.

THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN "A" YARD, TRACK 14 AND THE AREA HAD BEEN ISOLATED.  I ARRIVED ON SCENE APPROXIMATELY 1650 HOURS AND WAS ADVISED THAT FIRST RESPONSE HAD NOT BEEN TO THE CAR YET.  I INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE LIQUID LINE WITHOUT VALVE, CLOSURE FLANGE BOLTS/NUTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT ON THREE BOLTS, AND ONE BOLT WAS MISSING THE NUT.  I TIGHTENED THE BOLTS AND REPLACED THE MISSING NUT STOPPING THE LEAK.  FIRST RESPONSE ARRIVED AND NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED PRODUCT ON THE CAR AND GROUND.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLON LEAKED OUT.  THE CAR WAS OKAYED TO GO TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 1825 HOURS.

column168: ON MARCH 24,2003 AT 1525 HOURS THE TERMINAL NOTICED RAILCAR GATX 1381 VENTING AND MOISTURE FORMING AROUND THE PRESSURE RELIEF ON THE RAILCAR. THE TERMINAL SECURED SPILL PANS UNDER THE RAILCAR AND PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AROUND THE PRESSURE RELIEF. AT NO POINT DID THE MATERIAL REACH THE GROUND. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO OFFLOAD ONE FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUM OF THE PRODUCT IN AN EFFORT TO RELIVE PRESSURE. AT 1614 HOURS, ONE DRUM OF MATERIAL WAS OFFLOADED. THIS ACTION DID CAUSE THE MATERIAL TO STOP VENTING FROM THE RELIEF VALVE. IT WAS HOWEVER DETERMINED THAT MORE MATERIAL WOULD NEED TO BE REMOVED FROM THE RAILCAR AS THERE WAS NOT ADEQUATE ROOM FOR PRODUCT EXPANSION DUE TO WARM TEMPERATURES. AT 1910 HOURS A TANKER TRUCK ARRIVED AND 3.994 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE RAILCAR.

CITX 33431, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING VAPORS IN THE CLASSIFICATION YARD AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN WAYCROSS, GA.  THE TRAINMASTER REPORTED HE COULD SEE VAPORS COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND THERE WAS A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR.  THE AREA AROUND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE "B" TOWER DOWN WIND WAS EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTION.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE TRAINMASTER ADVISED THAT THE VAPOR RELEASE HAD STOPPED AND THE ODOR DISSIPATED.  HE INSPECTED THE DOME ON TOP OF THE CAR AND DISCOVERED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE VALVE PLUG WAS OUT.  HE CLOSED THE VALVE (TWO COMPLETE TURNS) AND INSTALLED THE PLUG.  THERE WAS NO MORE ODOR.  WHEN THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED THEY INSPECTED THE CAR FINDING NO OTHER SOURCE OF LEAKAGE.  THEY CONFIRMED THE VAPOR VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE PLUG WAS INSTALLED WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  NARRI SCORE: 130  5*(4+9+0) * (2+0)  CAUSE CODE 390

FOLLOWING  MAKING ALL CONNECTIONS FOR THE DELIVERY OF THE PRODUCT, THE DRIVER DID NOT AFFIX VELCRO SAFETY STRAPS TO THE HOSE CONNECTIONS THUS SECURING THE LOCKING ARMS OF THE FITTING IN PLACE.  THE HOSE VIBRATED LOOSE AND THE HOSE SEPARATED FROM THE RECEIVING LINE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO DISCHARGE ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  PRODUCT WAS PICKED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED WITH OTHER LIKE MATERIAL AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY.  CORRECTIVE ACTION FOR THIS INCIDENT IS THAT THE DRIVER WILL BE ISSUED ADEQUATE NUMBERS OF THE VELCRO SAFETY STRAPS AND HAVE THE USE OF THESE STRAPS REVIEWED, THIS IS A PREVENTABLE SPILL ON THE PART OF THE DRIVER.
CONSIGNEE STATED THAT THEY HAD ROOM TO HOLD THE LOAD IN THEIR STORAGE TANK, BUT THEY DID NOT.  OVERFILLED TANK BY 4 GALLONS ESTIMATED.

THE DOCKWORKER LOADED THE DRUM WITH CARDBOARD UNDER IT.  HE THEN LOADED A PALLET NEXT TO IT.  THE TRAILER THAT WAS BEING LOADED TO WAS LOWER THAN THE DOCK  (ABOUT 8"  LOWER).  WHILE BACKING OUT OF THE TRAILER THE RIGHT DRIVE TIRE SPUN THE CARDBOARD PULLING DRUM INTO SIDE OF THE WHEEL AND THE LUG NUT TORE THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  RIGHT AFTER, DOCKWORKER HELPED ME TURN THE DRUM ON IT'S SIDE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  IN THE FUTURE, WE WILL LOAD ALL DRUMS ON THE TAIL BEFORE SEALING THE TRAILER.

column168: ON MARCH 11, 2003 A RAILROAD TANK CAR UTLX 642914, LOADED WITH ENVIRONMETALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID, N.O.S. (ETHYLENE GLYCOL) , WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY (KCS) KANSAS CITY, MISSOURI RAIL YARD.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED VIA CHEMTREC AND ADVISED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS A LOOSE MANWAY COVER.  KCS MOBILIZED HAZMAT RESPONDER, INC.  OF OLATHE, KS, FOR THE ASSESSMENT AND PROPER SECURING OF THE MANWAY COVER AND BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. ADDITIONALLY, DURING THE RESPONSE AND TANK CAR ASSESSMENT, KCS FOUND THIS TANK CAR WITH THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP OFF AND HANGING UNDER THE TANK CAR BY THE RETENTION CHAIN.  THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AND THE CAP WAS APPLIED AND SECURED WRENCH TIGHT WITHOUT INCIDENT. NARRI=5(5+2+0) X (2+0) = 70  CODE = 568  *LOOSE MANWAY COVER/BOTTOM OUTLET CAP NOT SECURE

column168: IT APPEARS THAT A LOOSE FITTING EXTENDED BEYOND THE VALVE OF THE PORTABLE TANK VIBRATED LOSE DURING TRANSIT.  THE FITTING WHICH THREADS INTO THE 1/4 INCH BALL VALVE HAD A QUICK CONNECT DUST CAP ON THE END.  THE LOCKING EARS ON THE DUST CAP APPARENTLY KNOCKED THE VALVE HANDLE OPEN APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OF AN INCH ALLOWING THE NAPHTHA TO LEAK FROM THE TANK INTO THE BACK OF OUR VAN.  OUR DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE LEFT SIDE OF THE VAN AND IMMEDIATELY PULLED HIS TRUCK TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD TO INVESTIGATE.  HE WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE FROM THE SMELL THAT THE MATERIAL WAS NAPHTHA AND WAS COMING FROM THE PORTABLE TANK HE HAD ON BOARD.  SINCE THE TANK WAS ON THE BACK END OF THE TRUCK AND ACCESSIBLE, THE VALVE WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF STOPPING THE LEAK.  OUR DRIVER THEN USED THE SPILL KIT PROVIDED ON BOARD TO BEGIN CONTAINMENT OF THE SPILL BY FIRST BLOCKING THE MATERIAL TRAVELING DOWN THE ROAD TOWARDS SEWER OPENINGS.  THE SUN PRAIRIE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED TO HELP CONTAIN THE REMAINING SPILL.  AFTER THIS WAS COMPLETED, A PROFESSIONAL CLEAN-UP CREW REMOVED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS USED DURING CONTAINMENT PROCEDURES.  ALL MATERIALS WERE COLLECTED IN 55 GALLON DRUMS AND REMOVED.  THE MATERIAL WILL BE TESTED TO DETERMINE WHETHER IT IS HAZARDOUS AND SHIPPED TO A LICENSED DISPOSAL FACILITY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. TO AVOID THIS INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE, ANY PORTABLE TANK NOT CURRENTLY FITTED WITH A SAFETY VALVE WILL BE RETRO FITTED IMMEDIATELY.  THIS WILL HELP SECURE THE HANDLE FROM BEING OPENED DURING TRANSIT OR STORAGE.  ALSO, ALL FITTINGS WILL BE RE-CHECKED TO MAKE SURE THEY ARE SECURE PRIOR TO SHIPPING.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TWO ONCOMING NORTHWEST BOUND TRACTOR TRAILER UNITS TRAVELING THROUGH THE CURVE TOWARDS RAYNESFORD, MONTANA PASSING MY UNIT, THE RESULTS CAUSED SNOW DUST TO FLY AND SWIRL INTO THE WIND/AIR, TOTALLY BLOCKING MY VISION THROUGH THE WINDSHIELD, NOT SEEING THE LOAD COMPLETELY FOR WHAT SEEMED TO BE A LENGTHY TIME (BUT REALLY WAS A SHORT MINUTE).  SUDDENLY AT THE SAME TIME I FELT A TUG/PULL FROM THE BACK OF THE PUP TRAILER TANDEM TIRES OBVIOUSLY CATCHING THE RIGHT SHOULDER EDGE OF HIGHWAY AROUND CURVE, EVENTUALLY SLIDING THE ENTIRE PUP TRAILER UNIT INTO THE DITCH, UNHOOKING WHEN IT ROLLED AND STOPPED.  I TOOK MEASURES TO MINIMIZE AND ENSURE THE COMPLETE UNITS OF THE TRACTOR AND LEAD TRAILER WERE NOT DAMAGED OR PULLED INTO THE DITCH.  I DID THIS BY USING THE UPGRADE OF THE HILL TO GEAR DOWN SAFETY AS POSSIBLE AND NOT APPLY THE BRAKE TO AVOID A JACKKNIFE SITUATION UNTIL ALL UNITS CAME TO A COMPLETE STOP.  I SECURED THE HIGHWAY AND NOTIFIED AUTHORITIES AND THEN SLOWED DOWN LEAK SEEPAGE. I WAS LUCKILY UNHURT BUT SHAKEN UP.

I THEN DISPOSED OF ANY REMAINING MATERIAL USING THE PROCEDURES IN OUR DAMAGED MATERIAL PROCESSING PROGRAM.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0915 HRS ON FRIDAY, MARCH 28, 2003, ART BERNECKER (MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT) FOUND TACK CAR GATX 11104 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET ON TRACK #3 IN BROOKS AVENUE YARD.  HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE OUTLET TO CATCH THE FUEL OIL AND NOTIFIED CUSTOMER SERVICE REP NICK ZAJAC TO CONTACT UNITED REFINING IN ROCHESTER.  UNITED REFINING PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT 0925 HRS AND DISCOVERED THAT THE CAP ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS MISSING A GASKET.  THEY REPLACED THE GASKET AND SOAKED UP AS MUCH OF THE FUEL AS POSSIBLE.

WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION, LOCATED AT THE JUNCTION OF HIGHWAY 51 AND 78 IN BRUNEAU, ID, ONE PLASTIC LOCK AND LOAD TOTE CONTAINING TWENTY-SEVEN, FORTY POUND PLASTIC CONTAINERS WAS REFUSED BY THE CONSIGNEE. APPARENTLY, ONE, FORTY POUND CONTAINER WAS DAMAGED DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. APPROXIMATELY, SEVEN AND ONE-HALF POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE TOTE. OLYMPUS TECHNICAL SERVICES OF BOISE, IDAHO RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. OLYMPUS TECHNICAL SERVICES PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND FREE PRODUCT INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE USF REDDAWAY, INC. TERMINAL IN BOISE, ID, WHERE IT WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINING TWENTY-SIX CONTAINERS WERE RE-STACKED AND ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column42: POLYMERIC BEADS, EXPANDABLE, EVOLVING FLAMMABLE VAPOR
column168: ON MARCH 22, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 2130 HOURS, THE IKCES-22 WAS INVOLVED IN A SIDESWIPE AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN KANSAS CITY YARD.  INTERMODAL CONTAINERS NCEU 956187 AND NCRU 480306 SUSTAINED DAMAGE IN THE INCIDENT RUPTURING 2 CARDBOARD TOTES CONTAINING POLYMERIC BEADS, EXPANDABLE/9//UN2211/PG III AND SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 67 GALLONS.  THE KCSR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE SITE AT 2230 RECOVERING ALL BEADS FROM THE GROUND AND SECURING THE TORN TOTE WITH DUCT TAPE BY 0215 ON MARCH 23, 2003.  THE REMAINING TOTES WERE TRANSLOADED.  ENGINE SIDESWIPED 2 RAILCARS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON MARCH 15, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 1125 HOURS, THE SHREVEPORT KCS CREW FOUND UTLX 30044, A LOAD VINYLTOLUENES, STABILIZED, 3//UN2618//PG III, TO BE DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  AT 1145 HOURS THE CAR WAS ISOLATED, AND A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAKING VALVE.  THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN CONTRACT ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDER, SUMMIT ENVIRONMENTAL, ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1430 STOPPING THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP 3/4 TURN.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS. BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 1105 HOURS CSXT YARD CREW Y12311 OBSERVED TANK CAR GATX18384 WITH SIGNS OF FRESH LIQUID ON SIDES OF RAIL CAR.  BENNETT YARD MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE CORPORATIONS TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  THE SHIPPER, SOUTHERN STATES WAS CONTACTED AND RETAINED THE SERVICES OF RESCAR TO SECURE THE CONTAINER.  ONCE ON SITE, RESCAR NOTED THAT THE CAR HAD AN INCORRECT SIZE AND DETERIORATED FILL HOLE GASKET INSTALLED.  RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY (2) GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THE PROPER SIZE FILL HOLE GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE EXTERIOR SURFACE OF THE RAIL CAR WAS WIPED DOWN.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION ON MARCH 12TH.

column168: ON MARCH 18, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 1115 HOURS, CSX TRANSPORTATION TRAIN Q67417 HAD TANK CAR, GATX 31598, OBSERVED BY A PASSING TRAIN, TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  TANK CAR WAS SET OUT OF ITS TRAIN AND ISOLATED.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED SWS FROM ATLANTA, GA. TO INVESTIGATE.  UPON ARRIVAL SWS FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP TO BE LOOSE AND VALVE SLIGHTLY OPEN.  SWS CLOSED VALVE AND SECURED THE CAP.  THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS VERY SLIGHT.

column168: A CSX TRANSPORTATION CONDUCTOR WAS INSPECTING CARS IN THE WILLARD, OH, CSXT RAIL YARD AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS ON MARCH 20, 2003 AND OBSERVED TANK CAR UTLX 59612 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED TO THE SITE.  CHEMTRON WAS CONTRACTED TO RESPOND TO THE SITE.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED.  CSXT MGR. HAZMAT, J.D. CASEY RESPONDED AND FOUND THE TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE FLANGE, BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND TANK CAR. THE GASKET APPEARED TO BE DETERIORATED.  APPROXIMATELY 25,406 GALLONS (SHIPPERS ESTIMATE) OF PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED INTO HIGHWAY BULK CARRIERS AND TRANSPORTED TO THE CONSIGNEES FACILITY.

ON MARCH 20, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 HOURS, CSX TRANSPORTATION TRAIN Q36120 WAS SITTING ON THE SIDING AT MCGONIGLE, OH, WHERE A CONCERNED CITIZEN CALLED IN A CONCERN ABOUT AN ODOR AND A HISSING SOUND, BELIEVED TO BE FROM ONE OF THE CARS IN THE TRAIN.  PETROCLEAN, INC. WAS CONTRACTED AND RESPONDED TO THAT LOCATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF TANK CAR, SCMX 2904 PETROCLEAN FOUND 3 OF 8 MANWAY BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  CAR WAS SECURED BY TIGHTENING THE 3 MANWAY BOLTS.  PETROCLEAN ADVISED THERE WAS NO WETNESS ON THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR AND THERE WAS NO HISSING SOUND WHEN THEY ARRIVED.

column168: ON DAY OF INCIDENT, I NOTICED THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING A BLACK SUBSTANCE ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE DISPATCHER'S OFFICE.  I TOLD THE DISPATCHER TO CONTACT THE HAZMAT HOT-LINE AND TELL THEM ABOUT THE SITUATION.  A HAZ TEAM WAS DISPATCHED AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP.  PACKAGE APPEARED TO LEAK BENEATH INNER CONTAINER WAS NOT PROPERLY CLOSED AND SEALED.

WHILE UNLOADING, IT WAS NOTICED THAT A FORKLIFT BLADE HAD PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF DRUM NEAR THE SPILLING A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL.  WHEN DISCOVERED AN INVESTIGATION REVEALED THE DAMAGE WAS CAUSED DURING LOADING IN WHT.  I NOTIFIED THE WHT MANAGER OF INCIDENT AND PROVIDED DOCUMENTATION AND PICTURES OF THE EVENT.  HE WILL TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO RETRAIN AND DISCIPLINE THE EMPLOYEES INVOLVED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING ON THE TRAILER.  THE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A SMALL CRACK ON THE BOTTOM.  UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT, THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK AND CONTINUED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO THE OVERPACK WITH THE LEAKING DRUM.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED ON IT'S SIDE IN THE TRAILER.  ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PICKED UP THE DRUM AND AN ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND THE DOORS WERE OPENED FOR VENTILATION.  HAZMAT ONE RESPONSE OF OLATHE, KANSAS WAS CALLED TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP.  HAZMAT ONE RESPONSE DISPATCHED HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION OF ADDISON, ILLINOIS TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION PERSONNEL PERFORMED AN INVESTIGATION USING LEVEL C PROTECTION.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND WAS CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE DRUM FALLING BECAUSE OF IMPROPER BRACING.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WERE PLACED INTO A NINETY GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DURING LOADING ON OUTBOUND TRAILER, THE LOADER PLACED THE DRUM ON A NAIL THAT WAS RESTING ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE NAIL PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO SEEP FROM THE HOLE. THE LOADER WITH ASSISTANCE FROM DOCK PERSONNEL REMOVED THE DRUM AND PLACED IT INTO A PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM.  THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH CLAY ABSORBENT AND DISPOSED AS WASTE AT THE FACILITY.  NO FURTHER INCIDENT OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE LOADER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER CLEANING OF TRAILERS PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.
WHILE DRIVER WAS BLOWING DOWN THE HOSE THE FITTING POPPED OFF AND CAUSED SPILL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON US HWY 15, FOR UNKNOWN REASONS TRUCK LEFT ROADWAY VIA RIGHT SHOULDER TRAVELED APPROX 150' IN A ROADSIDE DITCH BEFORE OVERTURNING ON ITS RIGHT SIDE TRAVELING  ANOTHER 183' IMPACTING A DITCH CULVERT COMING TO REST ON ITS TOP.  THE FRONT SHELL OF THE TANK WAS PUNCTURED IN TWO PLACES AND THE OUTER SKIN ON RIGHT SIDE WAS ABRADED. SAFETY MEETINGS HAVE SINCE BEEN HELD AT ALL LOCATIONS TO DISCUSS EVENTS LEADING UP TO THIS ACCIDENT.  ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN CAUTIONED TO MATCH THEIR SPEED TO SURROUNDINGS AND NOT TO BECOME COMPLACENT IN THEIR JOBS.

DRIVER HAD STARTED THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED WHAT THE BLEEDER VALVE ON THE TRACTOR PUMP WAS LEFT PARTIALLY OPENED,  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON ASPHALT AND OIL DRY WAS USE TO ABSORB THE SPILLED PRODUCT. THE PLANT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE PRODUCT AND PLACED IT INTO A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE CUSTOMER STATED THAT THEY DISPOSED OF THE PRODUCT AND FORWARD THE PROPER PAPERWORK AND INVOICES TO CTL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  THE BALANCE OF THE LOAD WAS PUMPED OFF WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARDBOARD CARTON WAS FOUND IN THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE LEAKING, ONE QUART PLASTIC BOTTLE AND SEVEN AFFECTED, ONE QUART PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE DISCOVERED.  APPROXIMATELY EIGHT OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND ABSORBED BY THE CARDBOARD BOX.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE LID.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION.  THE LIDS ON THE EIGHT, ONE QUART PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE ALL TIGHTENED AND THE BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO THE WET CARDBOARD CARTON.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND WET CARDBOARD CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A TWENTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
NO REMARKS

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARDBOARD BOX CONTAINING TWO, ONE GALLON METAL PAILS WAS DISCOVERED ON THE BOTTOM OF A SKID INSIDE THE TRAILER.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT BOTH PAILS WERE LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE BOX.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE BOX BEING CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT ON THE SKID, PRESSING THE PAILS HANDLES DOWN AND CRACKING THE LIDS OF THE PAILS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, TYVEK SUITS, AND POLYABSORBENT TOWELS. column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EAST ON I-75 AND FAILED TO REDUCE SPEED UPON HIS APPROACH TO A DETAIL TRUCK WORKING ON THE ROAD, WAS FORCE TO BRAKE SUDDENLY AND STEER TO THE RIGHT HITTING THE DETAIL VEHICLE ON THE RIGHT REAR. OUR TRUCK THEN OVERTURNED SPILLING OIL AND COMING TO REST ON ITS RIGHT SIDE FACING EAST AND EJECTING OUR DRIVER. OUR COMPANY WAS AT THE SITE WITHIN THE HOUR TO START CLEAN UP, CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED WITHIN A WEEK. WE IMMEDIATELY SET UP A SAFETY MEETING, TO GO OVER WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND HAVE ALL THE DRIVERS REALIZES THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING ALERT, NOT USING CELL PHONES, SPEED AND WEARING SEAT BELTS. EVEN THOUGHT OUR COMPANY HAS A SAFETY MEETING EACH MONTH, WE ARE NOW HAVING THEM EVERY TWO WEEKS.

column168: WHILE SWITCHING TANK CAR GATX 61410 IN THE CLASSIFICATION YARD AT CUMBERLAND, MD, EMPLOYEES OBSERVED A WHITE, SMOKY VAPOR COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA WHERE IT COULD BE INSPECTED AND REPAIRED IF NECESSARY.  THE SHIPPER OF THE CAR WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO HAVE PERSONNEL COME TO THE YARD TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER CONTRACTED WITH AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO WORK ON THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR'S PERSONNEL DETERMINED THAT THE BOLTS BETWEEN THE FLANGES ON THE VAPOR LINE/PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AND THE MANWAY NOZZLE WERE CORRODED AND HAD BECOME LOOSE. THE SPACE BETWEEN THE TWO FLANGES ALLOWED VAPOR TO ESCAPE FROM THE BASE OF THE VAPOR VENT LINE. THE CORRODED BOLTS AND NUTS COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH.  SO THE BOLTS AND NUTS WERE REMOVED AND NEW BOLTS AND NUTS WERE INSTALLED.  ONCE THE NEW BOLTS WERE INSTALLED THE FLANGES SEALED AND NO FURTHER RELEASE OF VAPOR COULD BE DETECTED.  RESIDUE OF PREVIOUS LIQUID SPLASHES WAS EVIDENT ON THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THESE AREAS WERE CLEANED WITH A NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION.  AFTER THE REPAIR WAS COMPLETED, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: ON 3/14/03 @ 1400 HRS. CST, A BNSF CARMAN WORKING ON TANK CAR'S AIR BRAKES IN A YARD TRACK NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  THIS RELEASE STOPPED APPROX. ONE HOUR LATER, LOOSING AN ESTIMATED TWO GALLONS OF COMMODITY THAT EVAPORATED.  THE NEXT MORNING, A BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZMAT RESPONDER INSPECTED TANK CAR WITH A SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT TANK CAR WAS OVERFILLED & PRODUCT RELEASED VIA THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AS AMBIENT TEMPERATURES INCREASED.  ALSO NOTED DURING THIS INSPECTION WAS A PRE-EXISTING CONDITION OF A BROKEN CENTER SILL ON RTSX 24321, NECESSITATING ARRANGEMENTS FOR TOTAL PRODUCT TRANSFER TO A SUITABLE TANK CAR.  TRANSFER WAS PLANNED FOR THE MORNING OF 3/21/03.  ON 3/19/03 @ 1450 HRS. CST, A BNSF TRAIN CREW REPORTED PRODUCT WAS AGAIN LEAKING FROM RTSX 24321 THAT WAS STILL STANDING AT THE SAME LOCATION IN THE YARD.  BNSF RESPONDER DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT EXPANSION IN THIS OVERFILLED TANK CAUSED ADDITIONAL PRODUCT RELEASE.  PRODUCT TRANSFER TO ANOTHER TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ARRANGED & BEGAN AT 1930 HRS.  CST, 3/19/03 WITH COMPLETION BY 0700 HRS.  CST, 3/20/03.  AN ESTIMATED 200 GALLONS OF ADDITIONAL PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ON 3/19, REMEDIATED BY ABSORBENT WITH REMAINING PRODUCT EVAPORATING.  ONE OF THE BNSF CREW MEMBERS THAT ENCOUNTERED LEAKING TANK CAR ON 3/19, COMPLAINED OF PRODUCT INHALATION EXPOSURE & WAS EXAMINED/TREATED AT A NEARBY INFIRMARY EMERGENCY ROOM.  A PRESCRIPTION OF INHALANT & EYE DROPS PRESCRIBED TO EMPLOYEE AFTER CHEST X-RAY RESULTS INDICATED NO EXPOSURE DETECTION.  THIS BNSF EMPLOYEE WAS TO RETURN TO WORK FOR FULL DUTY THE FOLLOWING DAY, BUT INCURRED THREE LOST WORK DAYS.

ADMX 30175 WAS NOTED BY FRA INSPECTOR ANTHONY SCHNEIDER WITH PRODUCT VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE MANWAY DURING ROUTINE YARD INSPECTION.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, RESCAR, RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE CUT MANWAY COVER GASKET STOPPING THE RELEASE.

THE SHIPPER RESPONDED TO THE YARD TO ASSESS THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE AND OBSERVED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET WAS DETERIORATED.  THE DETERIORATED GASKET WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW GASKET AND THE CAP TIGHTENED, THIS HALTED THE RELEASE. column168: DRIVER WAS ASLEEP IN THE SLEEPER BERTH AT THE TRUCK STOP WHEN HE WAS AWAKENED BY A SECURITY GUARD BECAUSE OF AN ODOR THAT APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM THE CARGO TANK HE WAS PULLING.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION A VERY SLIGHT LEAK WAS DISCOVERED WITH THE TRAILER.  THE LEAK WAS SO SLIGHT, THAT A DECISION WAS MADE TO MOVE THE CARGO TANK APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE TO A TRIMAC FACILITY WHERE A TRANSFER COULD BE MADE WITHOUT AFFECTING THE FURTHER OPERATION OF THE TRUCK STOP.  WHILE ENROUTE TO THE TRIMAC FACILITY, THE LEAK WAS MONITORED TO ENSURE THAT IT WAS NOT BECOMING WORSE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TRIMAC FACILITY, ACTIONS WERE TAKEN TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING TRAILER INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK.  WHAT PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE TRAILER WHILE ENROUTE NOT THOUGHT TO BE AN ISSUE AS THE AMOUNT WAS VERY LITTLE AND WOULD HAVE EVAPORATED BEFORE ANY FURTHER ACTION COULD BE TAKEN. THE 1/2 GALLON NOTED ON THE REVERSE SIDE OF THIS REPORT WAS COLLECTED DURING THE TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT.  THE CARGO TANK HAS BEEN REPAIRED AND IS BACK IN SERVICE.

THIS REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED AS REQUESTED BY THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION ON MAY 9, 2003.  ON MARCH 7, 2003, CSX TRANSPORTATION (CSXT) RECEIVED A CALL FROM SELLERS, SC, FIRE DEPARTMENT CHIEF BILL WALLACE REGARDING TANK CARS LOCATED ON THE PRIVATELY OWNED SIDING AT PROVIDENCE ENVIRONMENTAL.  CSXT HAD DELIVERED THE RAIL CARS TO THE RESPONSIBLE PARTIES' CARE AND CONTROL SEVEN (7) DAYS EARLIER.  THE TANK CARS WERE NO LONGER IN TRANSPORT.  PROVIDENCE ENVIRONMENTAL TENDERED THE WAYBILL TO CSXT ON FEBRUARY 10, 2003.  THE BILLING INFORMATION, FROM PROVIDENCE, INDICATED THAT THE TANK CARS: GATX91466, GATX91503, GATX91526, GATX91532, GATX98031, GATX98032 AND GATX98033 WERE OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION AS AN EMPTY NON HAZARDOUS RAIL CAR.  THE CARS WERE DELIVERED BY CSXT TO PROVIDENCE ON FEBRUARY 28, 2003, ONTO TRACK OWNED AND CONTROLLED BY PROVIDENCE.  IN RESPONSE TO CHIEF WALLACE'S INQUIRY, CSXT IMMEDIATELY INVESTIGATED THE CAR CONTENTS, SHIPPER AND PROVIDED GUIDANCE TO ASSIST THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. ACCORDING TO CHIEF WALLACE,  THE RAIL CARS WERE "SMOKING FROM THE TOP" BUT HAD NO PLACARDS OR MARKINGS AND TAPE HAD BEEN APPLIED OVER THE AREA WHERE THE PRODUCT IDENTIFICATION NAME WOULD NORMALLY HAVE BEEN STENCILED.  AS SOON AS CSXT DETERMINED THE MOVEMENT HISTORY AND CONTENTS OF THE CAR, THAT INFORMATION WAS PROVIDED TO CHIEF WALLACE.  CSXT UTILIZED CHEMTREC TO ASSIST IN MAKING CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, PROVIDENCE ENVIRONMENTAL OF COLUMBIA, SC.  CHIEF WALLACE DECIDED AS A PRECAUTION TO EVACUATE APPROXIMATELY ELEVEN (11) NEARBY RESIDENTS UNTIL THE RELEASE WAS SECURED. NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED BY ANY OF THE RESIDENTS.  CSXT INFORMED PROVIDENCE OF THE COMMUNITIES' CONCERNS, THE POTENTIAL RISK TO THE COMMUNITY AND INSISTED THAT THEY RETURN TO THE SITE PROMPTLY TO PROPERLY SECURE THE RAIL CARS.  AFTER THE PERSISTENT URGING OF CSXT,  PROVIDENCE DISPATCHED REPRESENTATIVES TO THE LOCATION AND SECURED THE OPENINGS USING PLASTIC AND TAPE.  UPON FURTHER CAR RECORD MOVEMENT TRACING HISTORY OF OUR DATABASE, CSXT WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT THE CARS WERE PREVIOUSLY BILLED TO RESCAR IN RAINS, SC, AS RESIDUE TITANIUM TETRACHLORIDE.  ON THE DAY OF THE INCIDENT, MARCH 7, 2003, PROVIDENCE HAD APPARENTLY INITIATED A "CLEAN AND PURGE" OPERATION ON THESE RAIL CARS.  THEY USED A CRANE TO REMOVE THE PRESSURE PLATES ALONG WITH THE VALVE ASSEMBLIES ON EACH OF THEE CARS. ACCORDING TO PROVIDENCE STATEMENTS, THE CRANE WAS RENTED AND IN AN EFFORT TO SAVE MONEY, THE DECISION WAS MADE BY PROVIDENCE TO REMOVE ALL OF THE PRESSURE PLATES/VALVE ASSEMBLIES AT THE SAME TIME.  AFTER REMOVING THE PRESSURE PLATES.VALVE ASSEMBLIES, THE CREW CONTRACTED BY PROVIDENCE DEPARTED THE SITE FOR THE WEEKEND.

column168: SUPERIOR RECEIVED A SHIPMENT OF 3000 GALLONS OF SPENT SCRUBBER SOLUTION AND TRANSFERRED IT FROM THE CARGO TANK TO A BULK STORAGE TANK.  A SAMPLE WAS TAKEN FROM THE BULK STORAGE TANK AND DETERMINED TO BE OUT OF SPECIFICATION. UPON CONTACTING THE SHIPPER, IT WAS AGREED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS TO BE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CONSIGNEE.  SUPERIOR OPERATING PERSONNEL MADE THE REVERSE CONNECTIONS TO THE CARGO TANK.  THE TRANSFER PUMP WAS ENGAGED PRIOR TO OPENING THE BOTTOM (RECEIVING) VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK.  THE CAM LOCKS THAT HOLD THE FEMALE FITTING OF THE HOSE TO THE MAIL RECEIVER BELOW THE VALVE WERE LOOSE, AND THE PRESSURE IN THE HOSE FROM THE PUMP PUSHED THE FITTINGS APART, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN TO TWENTY GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE PUMP WAS STOPPED ALMOST IMMEDIATELY, AND RELEASE MITIGATION COMMENCED.  THERE WERE NO RESULTING INJURIES, EVACUATIONS, OR PROPERTY DAMAGE, AND ONLY MINIMAL COSTS ASSOCIATED WITH THE CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL ACTIVITIES.  AN INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT WAS CONDUCTED, AS REQUIRED BY SUPERIOR PROCEDURE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE OPERATOR RESPONSIBLE FOR THE INCIDENT FAILED TO FOLLOW PROPER PROCEDURE. OPERATORS ARE REQUIRED TO USE STRAPS TO SECURE CAM LOCKS FOR TRANSFER HOSE FITTINGS WHEN CONNECTED TO THE RECEIVING FITTING.  THE OPERATOR INVOLVED IN THIS FAILURE WAS PROVIDED SUPPLEMENTAL TRAINING REGARDING THE STRAPPING REQUIREMENT, AND HAS SINCE DEMONSTRATED ADHERENCE TO THE POLICY IN CONTINUING PRACTICE.

column168: ON THE MORNING OF 03/25/03 OIL TRANSPORT DRIVER SPOTTED HIS VEHICLE UNDER THE JP5 LOADING RACK AT THE CRANEY ISLAND FUELING DEPOT.  LOADING PROCEDURES IN PLACE AT THAT TIME WERE THAT THE DRIVER WOULD MAKE THE CONNECTIONS BETWEEN THE LOADING ARM AND TRAILER LOADING HEADS WHILE THE CRANEY ISLAND EMPLOYEE WOULD SET THE GALLONS TO BE LOADED ON THE CORRECT METER AND OPERATE THE "DEAD MAN" SWITCH WHICH ACTIVATED THE LOADING PUMP. THE FIRST COMPARTMENT WAS LOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THE SECOND COMPARTMENT WITH CAPACITY OF 1200 GALLONS WAS ALSO LOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  SOMEHOW FOR REASONS WHICH WERE NEVER DETERMINED, THE THIRD COMPARTMENT WHICH HAD A CAPACITY OF ONLY 1100 GALLONS HAD THE METER SET FOR 1200 GALLONS. THE TRAILER SCULLY OVERFILL SYSTEM "INTELLI CHECK" WORKED FINE AND SHUT OFF THE PUMP UPON PRODUCT REACHING THE OVERFILL SENSOR LOCATED INSIDE THE TOP OF THE TRAILER COMPARTMENT. HOWEVER, SINCE THIS WAS A SMALL CAPACITY COMPARTMENT AND THE PUMP WAS RUNNING FULL SPEED WHEN THE SENSOR INITIATED THE "SHUT DOWN" SIGNAL, THE COMPARTMENT OVERFILLED AND ABOUT A GALLON WAS DISCHARGED THROUGH THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM.  THIS PRODUCT HAD TO BE DRAINED FROM THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM INTO A BUCKET AND DISPOSED OF IN THE PROPER MANNER.  THERE WERE NO KNOWN SYSTEM FAILURES.  BOTH THE TRAILER AND TERMINAL SHUT DOWN SYSTEMS WORKED AS THEY WERE DESIGNED TO FUNCTION.  THIS WAS A HUMAN ERROR IN SETTING 1200 GALLONS INSTEAD OF 1100 GALLONS ON THE LOADING METER.

column168: ON MARCH 6, 2003 STARDUST TANK TRUCK LOADED WITH 8,000 GALLONS OF ETHANOL SKIDDED ON ICE AND ROLLED ON ITS SIDE NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF US ROUTE 20 AND US ROUTE 39.  THE TANKER DID NOT FAIL.  MINIMAL PRODUCT WAS RELEASED DURING TRANSFER TO ANOTHER VEHICLE/TANKER THAT WAS CLEANED.  INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND CHEMSOURCES. APPROXIMATELY 1000 GALLONS OF SNOW/WATER/ETHANOL WAS RECOVERED AND SENT TO DESIGNATED FACILITY.  COPY OF HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST IS ATTACHED. ACCIDENT ATTRIBUTED TO ROAD CONDITIONS - ALL EMPLOYEES TRAINED IN WINTER DRIVING SAFETY.

ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT OF AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S  AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S CORPORATION HAD INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACTED RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S. THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

THE OVERFILL WAS INSPECTED BY A LICENSED INSTALLER AND THE TRAILERS DROP FITTING WAS REPLACED AS THE DRIVER SAID IT WASN'T FITTING TIGHT. column168: STC DRIVER WAS MAKING LEFT TURN OFF WILLIAMS BLVD ONTO VETERANS HWY IN KENNER, LA.  THIS IS A CONTROLLED INTERSECTION FOR LEFT TURNS.  WHILE IN THE TURN A CAR TRAVELING NORTH ON WILLIAMS STARTED TO MOVE FORWARD AND STC DRIVER JERKED THE WHEEL TO MORE TO THE LEFT AND IN DOING SO THE UNIT ROLLED ON IT'S RIGHT SIDE.  THE DOT PROTECTION BOX STRUCK THE LEFT FRONT CORNER OF THE CAR.  THE IMPACT OF THE UNIT HITTING THE GROUND MUST HAVE LOOSENED THE FRONT WASHOUT CAP ON THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER FRONT WASHOUT CAP AREA STARTED TO DRIP APPROXIMATELY ONE DRIP EVERY THREE SECONDS.  THE KENNER, LA POLICE WAS ON SITE AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT.  THE STC DRIVER CALLED ME AND INFORMED ME OF THE INCIDENT.  I ASKED THE DRIVER TO MAKE SURE A BUCKET WAS UNDER THE DRIP.  AFTER TALKING TO THE DRIVER I CALLED EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.  ALL OTHER AGENCIES WERE THEN NOTIFIED INCLUDING NATIONAL AND LOUISIANA STATE.  NATIONAL RESP. #638997 LOUISIANA HOT LINE CASE #03-01497.  STC DRIVERS WILL BE COUNSELED AND ARE COUNSELED AT EVERY SAFETY MEETING ABOUT THIS ISSUE.  NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED AT THE TIME OF THIS INCIDENT.

column168: ON MARCH 3, 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HOURS FRA INSPECTORS JOEL ROBERTS AND JOE CONNELLY FOUND TANK CAR UTLX 650431 TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AREA APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) DROP EVERY TWO (2) MINUTES IN THE CSX TRANSPORTATION PARSONS AVENUE RAIL YARD. THE CAR WAS REPORTED TO THE CAR DEPARTMENT. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND BLUE FLAGGED. CONSIGNEE,(PPG, INDUSTRIES) WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. PPG SENT METROPOLITAN SERVICES TO INVESTIGATE AND REPAIR. MARVIN STOUT OF METROPOLITAN SERVICES FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CLOSURE PLUG WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. HE TIGHTENED THE PLUG AND THE LEAK STOPPED. CAR WAS SECURE.

ON MARCH 19,2003, TRUCK FLYT 4982 ARRIVED AT ABE WITH FREIGHT TO BE LOADED ON A/C FLYT 226.RAMP DOCK WORKER, TIM TOMEK, INITIALLY OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AND NOTICED AN ODOR BUT COULD NOT ISOLATE ITS LOCATION DUE TO THE ODOR DISSIPATING OUTSIDE. TIM THEN STARTED OFF LOADING THE TRUCK AND SENT THE BELLY HAZ CONTAINER DOWN THE BELT TO THE BELLY WORKERS ROBERT VORHOLY AND RICHARD COUKART. THEY PROCEEDED TO PULL SEVERAL CONTAINERS AROUND THE A/C TO LOAD. ONE OF THESE CONTAINERS WAS THE BELLY HAZ WHICH CONTAINED THE LEAKING SHIPMENT. RICH OPENED THE CONTAINER AND BEGAN PLACING FREIGHT AT THE OPENING OF BELLY 3/4 TO BE STACKED BY ROBERT WHO WAS INSIDE LOADING THE FREIGHT. THEY PLACED APPROXIMATELY 10 PIECES OF ASSORTED HAZ INTO THE A/C BELLY ALL CLASS 9 OR CLASS 6 PIECES. WHEN RICH NOTICED THAT A RING OF LIQUID FORMED AROUND THE ONE BOX SITTING ON THE BELLY OPENING. RICH PULLED THE PIECE BACK OUT OF THE BELLY OPENING SO THAT ROBERT COULD GET OUT OF THE A/C. ROBERT STEPPED INTO THE LIQUID WHEN EXITING THE BELLY, AND RICHARD PLACED THE BOX ON THE RAMP. THEY WENT FOR THE RAMP LEAD, JEFF GALLAGHER,TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. RICHARD TOLD JEFF ABOUT THE LEAKING SHIPMENT AND ROBERT SECURED THE AREA. ROBERT NOTIFIED THE MECHANIC, FLIGHT CREW, AND OTHER RAMP WORKERS. JEFF ARRIVED AND CHECKED THE AIRBILL, WHAT TYPE OF HAZ, AND GRABBED THE SHIPPERS DECLARATIONS FOR THE BELLY HAZ CONTAINER. JEFF CONTACTED ME AT THE ABH HUB FOR ADVICE. I TREVOR STEIGERWALT-ABH RAMP SUPERVISOR, TOLD JEFF TO CONTACT THE HAZ HOTLINE IMMEDIATELY AND FOLLOW THE ERCC FLIP CHART OF HAZ SPILLS UNTIL I CAN MAKE IT TO THE RAMP. I THEN INFORMED MY AREA MANAGER, DAVE KILLION OF THE SITUATION AT THE RAMP AND DEPARTED THE ABH HUB AT 0335. UPON ARRIVING AT THE RAMP AT 0355, JEFF HAD ALREADY CONTACTED ILN FLIGHT CONTROL, AND WAS BACK ON THE PHONE WITH THE HAZ HOTLINE. I QUICKLY STARTED INTERVIEWING THE RAMP WORKERS TO GET THEIR VERSIONS OF THE EVENTS LEADING UP TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE SPILL. I SPENT MORE TIME WITH RICHARD COUKART, ROBERT VORHOLY, AND TIM TOMEK ALL WHO WERE DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY INVOLVED WITH FINDING THE HAZ SPILL. I WANTED TO KNOW IF THEY WERE FEELING ANY EFFECTS OR SYMPTOMS FROM THE CONTACT WITH THE SPILL. AT 0415, I INSPECTED THE SPILL AREA TO ENSURE THAT EVERYONE AND EVERYTHING WAS SAFE AND SECURE. I THEN DETERMINED THAT ONLY TRACE AMOUNTS OF THE 6.1 LIQUID ACTUALLY CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE INSIDE OF BELLY 4. RICH SET THE HAZ IN THE DOOR OPENING AND IMMEDIATELY SAW SOME OF THE LIQUID DRIPPING OUT OF THE CORNER OF THE BOX. HE NOTED IT AS A FAUCET DRIPPING, HOWEVER, THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WAS ALREADY SOAKED FROM THE HAZ LEAKING ITS CONTENTS ONTO THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER ITSELF SEEMED TO BE WELL LOADED ORIENTATION ARROWS UP AND PROPERLY BLOCKED/BRACED. AT 0435, I CONTACTED ILN HAZ HOTLINE TO BRING THEM UP TO SPEED REGARDING THE A/C AND ALSO FIND OUT AN ETA ON THE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM DONNIE OSBORNE FROM THE HOTLINE INFORMED ME 1 HOUR AND THE HMHTTC WAS THE TEAM RESPONDING. I AL
TANK HAD VERY WEAK VENT ALARM.  TRAFFIC KEPT DRIVER FROM HEARING WHISTLE. SERVICE TECH REPLACED WHISTLE ON TANK.

ON 03/05/2003 AT 0048 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH AN ODOR OF KEROSENE WAS REPORTED AT DOOR "B" 33 OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS ELWOOD BOHL AND TERRY RUGGERIE DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE FIBERBOARD BOX TO CONTAIN 1 X 5 GALLON STEEL DRUM INSIDE OF A PLASTIC BAG WITH STRYROFOAM PACKING MATERIAL.  THE STEEL DRUM HAD A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE THAT WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURE WAS FOUND LOOSE INSIDE OF THE PLASTIC BAG THAT CONTAINED THE DRUM.  THE STEEL DRUM LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF ITS CONTENTS THROUGH THE OPENING ON THE TOP OF THE CAN.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.   THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0121  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

THE SMALLER FIBERBOARD BOXES EACH CONTAINED 1 X 3.4 OZ GLASS BOTTLE WITH A PUMP SPRAY TYPE CLOSURE OF "PERFUME." THE CLOSURES ON THESE BOTTLES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  ONE OF THESE BOTTLES WAS BROKEN AND LEAKED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS OF 3.4 OZ. . SHE REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. . THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. . THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED. . CLEAR OF SCENE:  1400 . THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

RAMP PERSONNEL NOTIFIED THE CREW CHIEF FOR AA FLIGHT 481 (GATE A19) THAT A PREVIOUSLY LOADED PASSENGER BAG WAS FOUND TO BE WET.  THE CREW CHIEF HALTED THE LOADING PROCESS AND NOTED AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE HAD LEAKED INSIDE THE BAG.  THE SUBSTANCE WAS ALSO FOUND THROUGHOUT SEVERAL LOCATIONS IN THE BELLY OF THE AIRCRAFT.  AT 1557 THE PASSENGER WAS LOCATED AND ESCORTED TO RAMPSIDE FOR IDENTIFICATION OF THE BAG AND CONTENTS.  THE SUBSTANCE WAS IDENTIFIED AS STP LEAD SUBSTITUTE IN THE PRODUCTS' ORIGINAL BOTTLE.  THE CONTENTS WERE REMOVED FROM THE BAG AND REPACKED INTO A NEW BOX.  THE SPILLED SUBSTANCE WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF.  TWO EMPLOYEES COMPLAINED OF SKIN IRRITATION DUE TO CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT.  THEY WERE TAKEN TO AA MEDICAL FOR FURTHER OBSERVATION.  I FORWARDED MEDICAL THE MSDS INFORMATION REGARDING PRODUCT CONTENT AND FIRST AID MEASURES (WASH SKIN WITH SOAP & WATER).  THE FLIGHT DEPARTED AT 1649 HOURS.

column168: NRC #639106 KY EPA INCIDENT #KY 0030889 SEE ATTACHED FOR FULL EXPLANATION: INCIDENT DESCRIPTION: THE RELEASE OCCURRED AT AROUND 11:30 A.M. AT THE ROYSTER-CLARK FACILITY LOCATED ON COMMERCE STREET IN FRANKLIN, KENTUCKY.  APPROXIMATELY 4,000 POUNDS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WERE RELEASED TO THE ATMOSPHERE FROM A 1,000-GALLON NURSE TANK DURING A HOSE CHANGING PROCEDURE.  AS THE EMPLOYEE WAS PREPARING TO DEPRESSURIZE THE WITHDRAWAL HOSE, HE WAS INTERRUPTED AND DISTRACTED BY OTHER EMPLOYEES AND A CUSTOMER.  AFTER A BRIEF CONVERSATION WITH THE EMPLOYEES AND CUSTOMER, THE EMPLOYEE TURNED BACK TO THE NURSE TANK AND PROCEEDED TO REMOVE THE HOSE.  AFTER TALKING WITH THE OTHER EMPLOYEES AND THE CUSTOMER, HE FORGOT TO BLEED THE PRESSURE FROM THE HOSE.  HE DID NOT NOTICE THE OPEN WITHDRAWAL VALVE AND SAWED INTO THE HOSE CAUSING THE CONTENTS OF THE NURSE TANK TO RELEASE.  THE EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY TRIED TO CLOSE THE WITHDRAWAL VALVE BUT FOUND THE VALVE HAD BEEN DAMAGED AND THE VALVE STEM WAS BENT.  THE BENT STEM PREVENTED THE VALVE FROM BEING CLOSED. A CALL WAS PLACED TO THE 911 DISPATCH AND THE FRANKLIN FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND SET UP A WATER FOG AND ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE THE VALVE.  ALL ATTEMPTS TO CLOSE THE VALVE WERE UNSUCCESSFUL AND THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK WERE ALLOWED TO DISSIPATE TO THE ATMOSPHERE. FIVE FACTORIES LOCATED IN THE INDUSTRIAL COMPLEX BEHIND THE ROYSTER-CLARK FACILITY WERE EVACUATED FOR ABOUT 2 1/2 HOURS.  THE FACTORIES EVACUATED WERE BONDED FIBERS INC., TYCO ELECTRONICS CORPORATION, PRINTERS INC., PETROFERM CONTRACT SERVICES INC., AND SILGAN PLASTICS CORPORATION. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE LOCAL 911 DISPATCH AT APPROXIMATELY 11:35 A.M.  CST.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED AT APPROXIMATELY 12:05 P.M.  CST AND THE STATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER AT APPROXIMATELY 12:15 P.M.  CST. CLEANUP AND REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES: ABOUT 4,000 GALLONS OF WATER WERE SPRAYED AT THE VAPOR CLOUD.  MOST OF THE WATER REMAINED ON THE SURFACE OF THE ROYSTER-CLARK LOT.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF WATER RAN OFF SITE DOWN A SMALL DITCH.  AT THE REQUEST OF THE KENTUCKY ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, ABOUT 30 GALLONS OF WATER WERE REMOVED FROM A SMALL DEPRESSION AT THE END OF A CULVERT.  THE WATER WAS PLACED IN DRUMS AND STORED IN CONTAINMENT AT THE ROYSTER-CLARK FACILITY.  THE WATER WILL BE LAND APPLIED.  IN AN EFFORT TO RECOVER SOME OF THE WATER FROM THE COMPANY LOT, A SUMP PIT DITCH WAS OPENED AT THE BASE OF THE HILL BELOW THE AREA WHERE THE WATER FOG WAS USED. THE PIT HAS BEEN MONITORED AND NO WATER HAS ACCUMULATED.  THE PIT IS NOW READY TO BE CLOSED. ROOT CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT: EMPLOYEE FAILED TO FOLLOW COMPANY PROCEDURES AND PERFORMED A LINE BREAKING PROCEDURE WITHOUT FIRST REMOVING PRESSURE FROM THE LINE. CONTRIBUTING CAUSES: A CONTRIBUTING CAUSE TO THE INCIDENT WAS THE DISTRACTION CAUSED WHEN THE EMPLOYEE STOPPED TO TALK WITH THE OTHER EMPLOYEES AND THE CUSTOMER. ANOTHER CONTRIBUTING CAUSE TO THE INCIDENT WAS THE WITHDRAWAL VALVE HAD A BENT STEM, POSSIBLY

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING WAS BEING UNLOADED OFF OF AN INBOUND AIRCRAFT THEN THE ODOR LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY WAS NOTICED.  FEDEX FLT-1473 (MEM-BOS) WAS BEING UNLOADED FROM THE BELLY WHEN UNLOADING PERSONNEL BEGAN TO NOTICE AN EXTREMELY PUGENT AND UNPLEASANT ODOR.  THE FIVE FEDEX EMPLOYEES THAT WERE AFFECTED BY THE ODOROUS SHIPMENT ARE AS FOLLOWS: GERRY MORAN, ROBERT HOPPE, ANDREW DEFILLIPPIS, SHAWN CARLEY, AND KIRSTEN WILLANDER.  THE SHIPMENT WHICH WAS INTERNATIONAL IN ORIGIN (BELGIUM) WAS ISOLATED AND CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AS A PRECAUTION. TWO MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS WERE REQUESTED  AND OBTAINED FROM BOTH SHIPPER AND RECIPIENT RESPECTIVELY.  THE FIRST MSDS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER WAS SOMEWHAT INACCURATE AND INCOMPLETE AS IT INDICATED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS A CORROSIVE IN PG II.  THE UN# SHOWN ON THE DOCUMENT 1610 WAS INVALID AGAINST THE DESCRIPTION SHOWN.  THE SECOND MSDS WAS MORE ACCURATE AND INDICATING THE MATERIAL CLASSIFICATION OF A CORROSIVE IN PG II.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT KATE ZAMPERELLI/FAA/BOS/CASFO AT APPROXIMATELY 11:30 (CST) ON 03/19/2003.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE PACKAGING FAILURE OCCURRED.  THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN PACKAGED BY THE SHIPPER USING APPROXIMATELY FIVE LBS OF DRY ICE AS A COOLING MEDIUM.  THE SPECIMEN VIALS CONTAINED BRAIN MATTER FROM BIRDS THAT WERE BELIEVED TO BE INFECTED WITH THE WEST NILE VIRUS.  THE VIALS WERE FURTHER OVERPACKED INTO A PLASTIC BOX WHICH WAS PLACED INTO A STYOFOAM SHIELD.  THE ENTIRE ASSEMBLY WAS THEN PLACED INTO AN OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX.  APPARENTLY THE SHIPPER PLACED THE DRY ICE INTO THE PLASTIC BOX AND SEALED IT.  THE BOX WAS NOT MANUFACTURED TO VENT INTERNAL GASES SO CONSEQUENTLY THE DRY ICE SUBLIMATED TO THE POINT WHERE THE PRESSURE BUILT UP IN THE PLASTIC BOX TO SUCH A DEGREE THAT IT CAUSED THE BOX TO RUPTURE WHICH IN TURN CAUSED THE TWO ADDITIONAL LAYERS OF PACKING TO FAIL AND TO ALLOW THE RELEASE OF THE SPECIMEN MATERIAL.  THERE WERE NO EXPOSURES OR INJURIES ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  PER 49 CFR 171.15(B) REGARDING THE IMMEDIATE REPORTING OF INCIDENTS INVOLVING INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCES, TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT RALPH ROMINE/FAA/IND/CASFO AT 22:36(CST) ON 03/18/2003 AND TO DR. SHANNA NESBY OF THE CENTER FOR DISEASE CONTROL, ATLANTA, GA AT 22:57(CST) ON 03/18/2003.

8:15 - AIRBORNE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED OF HAZ SPILL.  THE DRIVER SAID HE TOOK THE SHIPMENT OFF OF THE BELT AND PLACED IT ON THE FLOOR.  HE ADVISES HE DID NOT SEE ANYTHING LEAKING WHEN HE REMOVED IT FROM THE BELT.  HE SAID A MINUTE LATER HE LOOKED DOWN AND THERE WAS LIQUID RUNNING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX.  HE PLACED THE BOX IN A TOTE AND PUT IT OUTSIDE, THEN NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR.  THE AREA WAS EVACUATED.  THE AREA WAS MONITORED TO ENSURE NO ONE GOT NEAR THE SPILL.   ILN SENT A HAZ SPILL TEAM TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER HANDLING AND SAFETY.  HE HAS BEEN ADVISED TO NEVER MOVE A SPILLED SHIPMENT.

column168: FILE:3263-D SHIPPER: INLAND DIAMOND PRODUCTS AWB# TRY 10406752872 DFW.  ON 03/20/03 AT 2320 XENIA CITY POLICE CALLED TO REPORT THAT THE DRIVER OF A SEMI TRUCK/TRAILER (FLIGHT #6981) CARRYING ABX FREIGHT HAD RAN OFF OF US STATE ROUTE 35. (.1 OF A MILE FROM THE BELLBROOK EXIT) STRUCK A LIGHT POLE AND THE PRESENT TIME WAS STUCK IN A CULVERT.  PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIANS WILLIAM HENDERSON, TERRY RUGGERIE AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR CHARLES JONES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  AFTER SURVEYING SCENE AND DONNING PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THIS SHIPMENT FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THIS BOX TO CONTAIN 4 X 4 LITER PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH A PUSH AND TURN SCREW TYPE CLOSURES OF "ISOPROPANOL, 3, UN 1219, PG II".  THESE BOTTLES WERE SURROUNDED BY PACKING PEANUTS.  THE CLOSURES ON THESE BOTTLES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURE ON ONE OF THESE BOTTLES CAME OFF ALLOWING THE BOTTLE TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 3 OZ OF ITS CONTENTS.  NO OTHER SHIPMENTS WERE FOUND LEAKING AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT.  THIS SHIPMENT HAD CORRECT MARKINGS, LABELS, AND A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX SEALED AND PLACED THE SHIPMENT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE RECEIVER.  THE DRIVER OF THE SEMI WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND TREATED/RELEASED FOR MINOR INJURIES.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0477  A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  THERE ARE PICTURES OF THE LEAKING SHIPMENT ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

SORT HAD JUST BEGAN AND EMPLOYEE SAID THEY HAD LEAK IN TRAILER.  I RESPONDED AND REMOVED PACKAGE.  NO LEAKAGE IN TRAILER, SORTER WENT BACK TO WORK AND I PROCESSED, PLACING SALVAGED PRODUCT IN DRUM (SALVAGE) AND PROCESSING WET CARDBOARD BOX AND REMOVED FROM BUILDING.

column168: DICK DESPAIN, YARDMASTER, REPORTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP OF THE TILX 190017.  MANAGER ERNIE SIROTEK DISCOVERED LIQUID LINE VALVE PLUG LOOSE.  PLUG TIGHTENED FOR REPAIRS.  NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

JACK DEMPSEY, YARDMASTER, UNION PACIFIC, PHOENIX, AZ. REPORTED A STEADY STREAM OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANKCAR UTLX 201584 WHICH WAS LOCATED ON YARD 1 TRACK 8.  MR DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY UNION PACIFIC WAS NOTIFIED AND STATED HE WOULD CONTACT ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE, CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE FOR CLEAN UP PURPOSES.  MR. JOHNSON REPORTED THE TANKCAR WAS LEAKING DUE TO A LOOSE LIQUID LINE ASSEMBLY ON TOP OF THE CAR.  REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE LIQUID LINE ASSEMBLY AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

AT 1325 HRS ON 3-20-03, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT REGINALD STUBBLEFIELD, STRANG YARDMASTER HAD REPORTED TANK CAR ACFX 94906 TO BE LEAKING.  CAR WAS LOCATED ON THE MAINLINE TRACK, MILE POST 21, STRANG SUB DIVISION, ALONG HWY 146 & PORT ROAD; BAYPORT, TX.  CHECK OF WAYBILL INFORMATION INDICATED CAR WAS A RESIDUE EMPTY.  UPON RECEIVING INFORMATION, MGR LERCH REQUESTED THE RMCC CONTACT THE SHIPPER VIA CHEM-TREC.  MGR LERCH MET SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES LARRY PIPKIN, FACILITY PLANNING MANAGER AND FACILITIES PERSONNEL OF ODFJELL TERMINALS, (BAYTANK) AT THE SCENE.  MR PIPKIN INDICATED HIS PERSONNEL WERE UNABLE TO STOP THE RELEASE.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY MGR LERCH REVEALED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE FLANGE PLATE OF AIR AND LIQUID VALVES.  CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE A NITROGEN BLANKET WITHIN THE CAR FORCING RESIDUE VAPOR/PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE LOOSE FITTINGS.  UPON TIGHTENING THE 4 LIQUID AND AIR VALVE FLANGE NUTS APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TO 3/4 TURN EACH, THE CAR WAS SECURED FROM FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  UPON SECUREMENT OF THE CARS, MGR LERCH MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH MR PIPKIN TO HAVE IT RETURNED TO BAY TANK TO CLEAN RESIDUE PRODUCT FROM THE SIDES AND TOP OF THE CAR, AND HAVE RESCAR MOBIL RAILCAR REPAIR INSPECT THE CAR AND ENSURE IF WAS FULLY REPAIRED.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT.  THERE WAS NO IMPACT TO THE GROUND, DRAINS OR WATERWAYS.

MR SIROTEK STATED THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR WATERWAYS AFFECTED.

LEE NEAL, SENIOR MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR ADMX 30643, LOCATED IN THE J.R DAVID ROSEVILLE YARD, WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FORM THE TOP OF THE HATCH.  MR. NEAL REPORTED NO INJURIES OR WATERWAYS INVOLVED.  THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 302 IN THE DEPARTURE YARD. THE SHIPPER, DAVE DEDROSKY, ADM, WAS NOTIFIED AND ASKED TO INSPECT THE CAR PRIOR TO RELEASE.

KENNY AMOS, CENTENNIAL YARD, REPORTED TANKCAR APHX 2006 VENTED FOR THREE MINUTES.  THE TANKCAR WAS RESIDUE EMPTY.  TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL, CONTRACTOR, TO THE YARD TO INSPECT THE TANKCAR.  MGR. O'BRIEN CONFERRED WITH THE SHIPPER AND THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED ON ITS DESTINATION.

AT 1023HRS ON 3-11-03 WHILE CONDUCTING COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS, CTS MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT THE SIDES OF TANK CAR GATX 94796, LOCATED IN TRACK 4, ANGELTON, TX.  CLOSER INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE MANWAY COVER DUE TO A PINCHED AND MISALIGNED MANWAY GASKET.  UPON DETERMINING CAUSE OF RELEASE, MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, SCHENECTADY INTERNATIONAL, LOCATED IN FREEPORT, TX, AND SPOKE TO EMERGENCY COORDINATOR TERRY GRAHAM.  AFTER ADVISING MR GRAHAM OF THE INCIDENT, HE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE WITH FACILITY PERSONNEL TO REPAIR THE CAR.  THE ORIGINAL MANWAY GASKET WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW GASKET AND THE SIDES OF THE CAR WERE CLEANED.  AFTER THE NOTED CORRECTIONS WERE MADE, CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

DENNIS HATCH, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED RAILCAR PROX 41800 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM A HATCH ON TOP OF THE TANK.  JASON SORENSEN, SPECIAL AGENT, AND ALAN JENSEN, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WERE NOTIFIED. MANAGER JENSEN ADVISED PACIFIC WEST HAD BEEN CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE YARD. NECESSARY STATE AND CHEMTREC NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  PACIFIC WEST, CONTRACTOR COMPLETED REPAIRS TO A FLANGE GASKET THAT WAS NOT SEATED CORRECTLY AND A LOOSE FLANGE BOLT.  MR. JENSEN ADVISED THE ESTIMATED QUANTITY OF PRODUCT LOST AT ONE GALLON OR LESS.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE UPDATED.

ARTURO TALAMANTEZ, CAR FOREMAN, ADVISED A YARD WORKER REPORTED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR COMING FROM TANKCAR UTLX 80564, LOCATED IN THE YARD IN EAGLE PASS, TX.  PAUL PERSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MR. TALAMANTEZ STATED THE EAGLE PASS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND WAS RESPONDING. MGR PERSON DETERMINED THAT THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE PACKING GLAND WAS LEAKING AND THREE BULL PLUGS WERE ONLY HAND TIGHT.  REPAIRS WERE MADE AND THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED OF AN ODOR IN THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARD.  MR. SIMPSON RESPONDED AND AFTER INSPECTING SEVERAL TANKCARS, A SMALL LEAK FROM THE TANKCAR CELX 11223 WAS DISCOVERED.  THE BOTTOM VALVE WAS LEAKING AND AFTER IT WAS TIGHTENED THE LEAK STOPPED.

ISAAC SHANNON, SECURITY GUARD, REPORTED CONTAINER CBHU 307198 WAS LEAKING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND WAS LOCATED AT SLOT 219 EAST OF TRACK 805 OF THE ICTF YARD.  DUFFY EXON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER DETERMINED THAT ONE DRUM IN THE THIRD ROW IN FROM THE NOSE HAD LEAKED.  THE DRUM HAD RUBBED AGAINST THE TIE DOWNS BECAUSE THE 3/8TH INCH PLYWOOD WAS NOT THICK ENOUGH TO LIFT THE DRUM ABOVE THE TIE DOWNS.  THE DRUM FAILED RIGHT ABOVE THE ROLLING RING.  IT WAS OVERPACKED AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: PAM GINGERICH, FRA HAZ-MAT INSPECTOR NOTIFIED LANE A SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A SUSPECTED LEAKING TANK CAR IN TOPEKA, KS.  GATX 97074 APPEARED TO BE LEAKING FROM AN UNDETERMINED LOCATION IN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THE PLUG FOR THE SAMPLE VALVE WAS ALSO MISSING.  MR. SEKAVEC NOTIFIED UPRR'S RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER TO FACILITATE CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER.  MR. SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH JACK CURRY, MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR FARMLAND INDUSTRIES.  MR. CURRY ADVISED MEARS FERTILIZER HAD UNLOADED THE CAR.  MR. SEKAVEC WAS IN OBERLIN, KS. MR. MEARS STATED HE DID NOT HAVE ANYONE THAT COULD LOOK AT THE CAR.  MR. SEKAVEC THEN CONTACTED MR. CURRY AND MADE THE SAME REQUEST.  MR. CURRY ADVISED THAT THEY HAD NO ONE TO RESPOND EITHER AND SUGGESTED THEIR CONTRACTOR.  MR. SEKAVEC REQUESTED HAZ-MAT RESPONSE (CONTRACTOR) TO RESPOND AND INSPECT THE CAR.  AFTER MAKING THE INSPECTION, PERSONNEL FROM HAZ-MAT RESPONSE ADVISED THE PLUG WAS INDEED MISSING FROM THE SAMPLE LINE BUT THE VALVE WAS CLOSED.  THEY ALSO STATED THAT THE PACKING NUT AROUND THE SLIP-TUBE GAUGING DEVICE WAS ALSO LOOSE.  THE PLUG WAS REPLACED AND THE PACKING NUT WAS TIGHTENED SO THAT THE CAR COULD CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DRIVER (JERRY PRIETO) WAS WESTBOUND ON FARMROAD 2397 TURNING LEFT (SOUTH) ON FARMROAD 1172 WHEN THE TRUCK TRACTOR AND SEMI-TRAILER OVERTURNED.   THE AGRICULTURAL DRY FERTILIZER (IMPREGNATED WITH 144 POUNDS OF TRIFLURALIN HERBICIDE) SPILLED FROM THE TARPAULIN COVERED BIN SEMI-TRAILER INTO A DRY DITCH ADJACENT TO THE ROADWAY.  TRIFLURALIN HAS A 10 POUND REPORTABLE QUANTITY.  ON 3/11/2003 AT ABOUT 12:20 PM, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT #639108).  MR. RICHARD HARRIS WITH THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.  THE FERTILIZER AND ABOUT 2 INCHES OF SOIL WERE PLACED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER AND WILL AGRONOMICALLY APPLIED TO AGRICULTURAL PASTURE LAND.  THE TRUCK TRACTOR AND SEMI-TRAILER WERE TOWED AWAY AND THE DRIVER RECEIVED A CITATION FOR THE ACCIDENT. DRUG AND ALCOHOL POST-ACCIDENT TESTS WERE DONE, AND THE RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE.  THE DRIVER WILL ATTEND A DEFENSIVE DRIVER TRAINING PROGRAM.

DRIVER, DAVE KAPP, WAS DELIVERING A PACKAGE TO 365 HILL CITY ROAD, CRANBERRY, PA.  THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING SOME WHITE CRYSTALS AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY.  DAVE ASKED THE CUSTOMER WHAT WAS IN THE PACKAGE AND SHE STATED SHE DID NOT KNOW.  DAVE WAS HEADING TO HIS NEXT DELIVERY WHEN HE FELT HIS ARMS BURNING AND HIS CHEST.  HE CALLED CENTER AND SAID HE WAS ON HIS WAY BACK TO BUILDING THAT HIS SKIN WAS BURNING.  WE RETRIEVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE CONSIGNEE AND FOUND IT WAS A CORROSIVE MATERIAL THAT WAS NOT MARKED. DAVE WAS SENT FOR MEDICAL TREATMENT TO WORKER'S CARE, SENECA, PA.  A MSDS WAS OBTAINED FOR THE MATERIAL AND THE PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP BY RESPONDER.  TEMP ID# 032501P.  DRIVER IS RECEIVING CARE FOR 1ST AND 2ND DEGREE BURNS.

PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS GARY GRAGG AND WILLIAM  HENDERSON DONNED PROPER PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THIS BOX  FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE FIBERBOARD BOX TO CONTAIN 2 X 1 QUART METAL PAINT CANS WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES OF "COATING". ONE OF THESE CLOSURES WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THERE WERE FIVE EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED. AT 1930 HRS ON 3-29-03, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT RANDY LUCE, DIRECTOR TERMINAL OPERATIONS, HAD REPORTED COVERED HOPPER CAR MP 710711 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE CENTER DUMP.  THE HOPPER CAR WAS LOCATED IN THE ENGLEWOOD YARD, BOWL TRACK 3.  UPON BEING NOTIFIED, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY CONFERRED WITH MR. LUCE, WHO ADVISED THE CAR DEPARTMENT HAD THE TOOLS REQUIRED TO SECURE THE DUMP, HOWEVER DID NOT HAVE THE CORRECT PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT TO WORK ON THE CAR.  MGR. LERCH RESPONDED AND HAD RMCC MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC.  INSPECTION OF THE RAILCAR DETERMINED THAT THE CENTER COMPARTMENT BOTTOM DUMP WAS FOUND TO BE MECHANICALLY DEFECTIVE, WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT. EFFORTS TO MAKE TEMPORARY REPAIRS WERE UNSUCCESSFUL AND THE RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED UNTIL WHEN REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.  ON 03/30/03 MGR. LERCH MET WITH SHELBY STARTZ, HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL, AND GRADY WINSLOW, AMERICAN RECOVERY TO REPAIR THE CAR AND RECOVER THE PRODUCT.  MR. LERCH ADVISED THE CENTER BOTTOM DUMP HAD BEEN TEMPORARILY REPAIRED/SEALED FROM ANY FURTHER RELEASE AND THAT APPROXIMATELY FIVE YARDS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED IN BOWL TRACK 3 WITH A TOTAL OF APPROXIMATELY 7-8 YARDS OF PRODUCT MIXED WITH SOIL HAVING BEEN RECOVERED AND SECURED FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER TIME. THE CAR WAS THEN SET-OUT FOR COMPLETE OFF LOADING AND FURTHER HANDLING BY THE CAR DEPARTMENT. NARRI:  5(5+1+0) X (3+0) = 90
